# Work

Drive a single planctl task to completion. The task runs inside a fresh `worker` subagent so the main context stays lean; the main context only orchestrates (claim → spawn worker → verify done).

The tier (reasoning effort) was already chosen at planning time and is persisted on the task. Keeper reads it from its own projected Task data and loads the matching `claude/work-plugins/<tier>/` plugin before claude boots — so exactly one `work:worker` agent is in scope per session and this skill spawns it as a bare literal.

## When to invoke

The human said "work", "/work", or passed an existing planctl task id to run. Accepts a single input shape:

- `fn-N-slug.M` — task id, run just this one task

---

## Phase 1 — Claim the task

**Shared-tree principle (read first):** This repo runs concurrent agents and the human's in-progress work in parallel — at any moment the working tree may carry uncommitted changes that have nothing to do with this task. Any file you didn't write through this session belongs to someone else: never auto-stash it, never classify it as in-/out-of-scope for the worker, never commit it. Authoritative attribution comes from `jobctl session-state`'s `session_files` field (subagent writes share the parent session_id in hookctl's tracker, so the orchestrator's session_files already covers worker output) — anything in `status_porcelain` but not in `session_files` is someone else's territory.

One call asserts invariants, claims the task (`todo` → `in_progress`), and returns the full worker briefing — no `detect`, no separate `show`/`cat`, no `cd`, no standalone `render-spec`. `claim` resolves the owning project cwd-agnostically (scans configured `roots`), so this works from any directory:

```bash
planctl claim <task_id>
```

**On a typed error** — envelope `{"success": false, "error": {"code", "message", "details"}}` — surface `error.message` verbatim and stop. The `code` covers every reject (`BAD_TASK_ID`, `TASK_NOT_FOUND`, `AMBIGUOUS_TASK_ID`, `TASK_DONE`, `TASK_BLOCKED`, claimed-by-another, unmet deps). `claim` fails loud on bad input — automation always supplies a valid id, so there's no empty-args branch to handle. For an `AMBIGUOUS_TASK_ID` (same id in multiple projects), re-run with `planctl claim <task_id> --project <path>`.

**On success**, read the 11-key briefing envelope and pin these in working memory for the phases below:

- `task_id`, `epic_id` — ids.
- `target_repo` — absolute path the worker cds into for code work (may equal `primary_repo` for single-repo tasks).
- `primary_repo` — absolute path of the planctl state repo (where the `.planctl/` commit lands).
- `tier` — persisted tier (`medium | high | xhigh | max`). Keeper already used this to load the matching `work-plugins/<tier>/` plugin; this skill quotes it back for transparency but never picks it.
- `task_spec_md`, `epic_spec_md` — the spec markdown the worker briefing needs; no re-fetch.
- `task_state`, `epic_state` — runtime + epic metadata (status, title).
- `snippet_context` — pre-rendered substrate prose (folded-in `render-spec`); empty string when the task has no curated substrate.

Quote back a one-line summary so the human sees state is loaded, naming the persisted tier for transparency: *"working `fn-1-foo.3` at `<tier>`: <title>."*

---

## Phase 2 — Run task

The task is already claimed and the briefing is in working memory (Phase 1). The worker spawns into `target_repo` from the envelope.

### 2a. Spawn worker subagent

Use the Task tool to invoke the `work:worker` subagent with a minimal config-only prompt. The worker's shared body lives in `apps/planctl/agent-templates/worker.md.tmpl` (rendered into `claude/work-plugins/<tier>/agents/worker.md` per tier — exactly one tier-plugin loads per session, set by keeper pre-boot). Do **not** paraphrase those phases here.

**Tier is already chosen and loaded.** The planner (`/plan:plan`) picks tier per task at decomposition time and writes it into the scaffold YAML; keeper reads the persisted tier from its own projected Task data and adds `--plugin-dir claude/work-plugins/<tier>` to claude's launch line. By the time this skill runs, exactly one `work:worker` is in scope for the session, pinned to that tier's `claude-opus-4-7` + matching `effort:` via the agent file. This skill never picks or persists a tier — the planner owns the cognitive decision, keeper owns the runtime routing, and the spawn target is a bare literal.

**Snippet context for the worker.** The `snippet_context` field from the Phase 1 envelope is the inheritor-tier substrate, already resolved: the planner authored `task.snippets` / `task.bundles` (and inherited `epic.snippets` / `epic.bundles`) at planning time, and `claim` folded in the `render-spec` resolution so this skill never shells it separately.

- **`snippet_context` is non-empty:** prepend a `## Snippet context` section to the worker brief, immediately above the existing `## Task` material — the envelope value is the section body. The worker's agent spec documents this section as authoritative pre-rendered substrate (do not re-fetch via `find-snippets` / `show-snippet` / `render`).
- **`snippet_context` is the empty string:** task has no curated substrate set. Skip the `## Snippet context` section entirely — do not emit a blank header.

**Prompt template:**

```
Implement a planctl task.

TASK_ID: <fn-N-slug.M>
EPIC_ID: <fn-N-slug>
PLANCTL: planctl
REVIEW_MODE: none
TARGET_REPO: <absolute path to target_repo, or same as PRIMARY_REPO if task.target_repo is null>
PRIMARY_REPO: <absolute path to the primary_repo (planctl state repo)>

## Snippet context
<verbatim `snippet_context` value from the Phase 1 claim envelope, omitted entirely when empty>

## Task spec

<verbatim `task_spec_md` value from the Phase 1 claim envelope>

## Epic spec

<verbatim `epic_spec_md` value from the Phase 1 claim envelope>

## Task

Follow your agent spec. If your turn opens with a directive from this skill instead of this template, the directive overrides the phase scaffolding.
```

The `## Snippet context`, `## Task spec`, and `## Epic spec` sections sit between the configuration block and the `## Task` directive so the worker reads curated substrate and the full specs (already paid-for by the parent's `claim` envelope) first, and the action directive last. The worker's agent spec Phase 1 reads `## Task spec` and `## Epic spec` from the brief instead of shelling `planctl cat` twice — one fewer round trip per worker spawn. Both `worker.md.tmpl` and the worker's own Phase 1 / Phase 1.5 reference these sections by name. Omit any section entirely when the corresponding envelope field is empty (matches the `snippet_context` empty-string rule).

Populate `TARGET_REPO` and `PRIMARY_REPO` directly from the Phase 1 claim envelope — both are already fully resolved to absolute paths:
- `TARGET_REPO` — the envelope's `target_repo`.
- `PRIMARY_REPO` — the envelope's `primary_repo`.

Invocation:

```
Task(
    subagent_type="work:worker",
    description="Work <task_id>",
    prompt="<prompt above>"
)
```

`subagent_type` is a bare literal — no f-string, no tier suffix. Keeper already loaded the right tier-plugin pre-boot, so `work:worker` resolves to exactly one agent in scope (the tier picked at planning time). The agent file owns the model and effort — do **not** pass `model=` on the spawn. The worker returns a concise summary (what was implemented, files changed, tests run if any). Don't re-read files the worker already touched — trust the return value.

**Capture `worker_agent_id` from the Task tool result.** The result string ends with `…agentId: <hex> (use SendMessage with to: '<id>' to continue this agent)`. Extract with the regex `agentId:\s*([a-f0-9]{10,})` (the agent_id has no newline before it — `re.search`, not `re.match`). Pin the captured hex string in working memory as `worker_agent_id` for Phase 2b's warm-resume path. If the regex doesn't match (very rare), set `worker_agent_id = None` and continue — Phase 2b's cold path handles missing-id case.

### 2b. Verify done

```bash
planctl show <task_id>
```

**Two-commit-per-task shape:** Worker Phase 5 runs `jobctl commit-work "<msg>"` first → commit #1 is source (`feat(scope): ...` carrying `Task: <id>` trailer). Worker Phase 6 runs `planctl done`, which emits a `planctl_invocation` envelope; the hookctl-mutation hook lands commit #2 (`.planctl/` state, subject `chore(planctl): done <task_id>`). Source-before-state in history: source is "here's the work," state is "…and it's accepted." If `status: done` after the worker returns, both commits are guaranteed to be in place — `done` cannot fire before the source commit lands.

If `status: done`, continue to Phase 3. If not:

- `in_progress` → harness drop detected (worker vanished mid-`tool_use` before it could complete commit-then-done). The recovery budget is **5 attempts (1 spawn + 4 retries)** — each warm SendMessage resume and each cold fresh-respawn counts one attempt toward the budget. `RESUME_EXHAUSTED` fires only after the 5th attempt fails.

  **Cross-session counting (best-effort, per-invocation).** The warm path has an in-memory attempt counter scoped to this invocation: increment it once per SendMessage resume, and after the 5th drop flip to `RESUME_EXHAUSTED`. The cold path has **no shared in-memory counter** — a separate `/plan:work` invocation that opens with the task already `in_progress` cannot see prior invocations' attempts. So the budget is **best-effort per-invocation**: within one invocation it is enforced exactly (warm retries are counted); across separate cold-resume invocations each fresh `/plan:work` run gets its own budget (one cold spawn = one attempt, and a re-run after that cold spawn drops again starts fresh). There is no attempt-count field persisted on the task — the budget deliberately rides invocation-local memory, trading cross-invocation precision for zero new state. A task that genuinely cannot make progress will surface repeatedly as `in_progress`; the human eyeballs the pattern and blocks it by hand rather than relying on a persisted cross-session cap.

  **In-session vs cross-session split.** If `worker_agent_id` was captured in Phase 2a **this invocation**, you're in-session — go **warm**. If `worker_agent_id` is unset (this is a separate `/plan:work` invocation that opened with the task already `in_progress` — orchestrator has no shared memory across invocations), you're cross-session — go **cold**. The rule: Phase 2a didn't run this invocation but Phase 2b sees `in_progress` → cross-session.

  **Warm path (in-session, `worker_agent_id` set):**

  1. Compute state-diff:

     ```bash
     jobctl find-task-commit <task_id>
     planctl show <task_id>
     ```

     If `find-task-commit` returns a non-empty `commits` list, the source commit landed; only `planctl done` remains. Otherwise the worker dropped mid-implementation.

  2. Build a tight resume directive — imperative, no narrative:
     - **No source commit landed:** *"Resume task `<id>`. Finish implementation, run tests, `jobctl commit-work`, `planctl done`."*
     - **Source commit landed but status still `in_progress`:** *"Source commit `<sha>` landed. Run `planctl done <task_id> --summary "..."` now."*

     The worker's agent spec already says "resume directives outrank phases" and "do not re-anchor" at the top — don't repeat those here. Keep the directive a one-liner that names the next concrete action.

  3. Send the directive (fire-and-forget — returns immediately):

     ```
     SendMessage(to=worker_agent_id, message=<directive>)
     ```

     SendMessage error envelope `{"success": false, "message": "No agent named '<id>' is currently addressable..."}` means the agent_id is dead/invalid — fall through to the cold path.

  4. Wait for the worker to finish. On `done` → continue to Phase 3. On `blocked` → BLOCKED short-circuit. If the worker drops again (status stays `in_progress`), increment the invocation-local attempt counter and loop: re-send a fresh resume directive (warm) as long as `worker_agent_id` is still addressable, falling through to the cold path on a SendMessage error. Only after the **5th** attempt in this invocation drops do you `planctl block <task_id> --reason "RESUME_EXHAUSTED: harness dropped through 5 attempts (1 spawn + 4 retries) on Phase 2b warm-resume"` and stop.

  **Cold path (cross-session, or warm SendMessage error):**

  Keeper policed tier before claude booted (a missing or unsupported tier fails loud with `task <id> has unsupported tier ...` — fn-594), so by the time this cold path runs the tier-plugin matching `task.tier` is already loaded and `work:worker` resolves to the right agent. No tier-read here, no fallback heuristic — the work-plugin layer owns tier routing.

  1. Shell `planctl worker resume <task_id>` once and read the success envelope's `prompt` field — the CONTEXT preamble to pass into the spawn.

  2. Spawn ONE fresh worker:

     ```
     Task(subagent_type="work:worker", description="Resume <task_id>", prompt=<envelope.prompt>)
     ```

     No `model=` kwarg — the agent file owns the model. The "harness-dropped predecessor" branch inside the worker agent spec's Phase 1 handles detection (uses `jobctl find-task-commit` + `jobctl session-state` to decide whether to skip ahead to `planctl done` or continue from Phase 3).

  3. Re-check `planctl show <task_id>` after the spawn returns:
     - `done` → continue to Phase 3.
     - `blocked` → BLOCKED short-circuit.
     - `in_progress` (the cold spawn dropped) → this cold-resume invocation has spent its single attempt. The cold path holds no cross-invocation counter, so do NOT block — surface the `in_progress` state to the human verbatim and stop. A fresh `/plan:work` re-run takes another attempt under the best-effort budget; a task that genuinely can't progress surfaces repeatedly as `in_progress` and the human blocks it by hand.

  **`BLOCKED:` short-circuit:** if the worker returns a `BLOCKED: <category>` message at any point, immediately surface the breadcrumb and stop. Semantic failures bypass the recovery flow entirely.

- `blocked` → worker escalated; surface the `BLOCKED: <category>` breadcrumb from the return value, stop.
- Anything else → unexpected, surface it and stop.

---

## Phase 3 — Quality (best-effort)

After the task completes, run project tests/lints if a clear command is discoverable. Best-effort — don't block the ship on a missing test runner. **Project tests always run** — deterministic checks are never skipped.

Check for common entrypoints:

- `pyproject.toml` present → `uv run pytest` (or the project's test script if defined)
- `package.json` with `scripts.test` → `pnpm test` / `npm test` / `bun test` per manifest
- `build.zig` present → `zig build test`
- `Cargo.toml` → `cargo test`
- Epic spec has a `## Quick commands` section → run its bash lines

If no clear test command is present, skip silently and note it in Phase 4 output (*"no project test runner detected — quality phase skipped"*).

If tests fail, surface the failure verbatim. Do not auto-fix — the human makes the call.

---

## Phase 4 — Ship

1. **Validate the epic**:

   ```bash
   planctl validate --epic <epic_id>
   ```

   If `valid: false`, surface errors verbatim and stop (no auto-fix).

2. **Verify the tree is clean of session work.**

   Read the combined git + session state yourself — never infer "everything committed" from the worker's narration alone (subagent result-overflow can truncate output):

   ```bash
   jobctl session-state
   ```

   Read `status_porcelain` (uncommitted files in the *whole tree*) and `session_files` (paths this session — orchestrator + subagents — touched). Subagent writes share the parent session_id in hookctl's tracker, so `session_files` already covers worker output without per-subagent lookups.

   **Attribution rule:** trust `session_files` as your scope of authority. Anything in `status_porcelain` that is *not* in `session_files` is concurrent-agent or human work — leave it alone. Never inspect, classify, or commit those files.

   Under the commit-before-done worker contract (worker Phase 5 → Phase 6), `status: done` is impossible without the source commit having landed first. So:

   - If every path in `session_files` is committed (clean intersection with `status_porcelain`), continue to step 3.
   - If any path in `session_files` is *still* dirty, this is an unexpected state — surface `jobctl session-state` verbatim and **stop**. Do not auto-resume, do not auto-commit. The contract says `done` ⇒ committed; if reality disagrees, the human investigates.

3. **Do NOT close the epic.** `planctl epic close` stays manual.

4. **`jobctl commit-work` failures surface as BLOCKED.** Lint, commit, or push failure → worker returns `BLOCKED: TOOLING_FAILURE` with the verbatim envelope JSON; Phase 2b short-circuits on BLOCKED. The human resolves (fix the lint runner, rebase/pull, fix auth, etc.) and re-runs `/plan:work`; on re-run, Phase 2b's harness-drop path picks up via `status: in_progress`. The flock at `$GIT_COMMON_DIR/jobctl-commit.lock` makes the intra-host commit race impossible; cross-host pushes that fail are rare and deserve a human eyeball.

## Phase 5 — Report

One-line summary:

> `fn-1-foo.3` done. commit: `<sha>`. tests: <pass|skip|fail>. epic progress: M/N tasks done.

Include per-task commit sha from worker return. No menu, no follow-up prompts.

---

## Guardrails

- **Never auto-closes the epic** — `planctl epic close` stays the human's call.
- **Commit-then-done worker contract.** Worker Phase 3 runs tests, Phase 5 runs `jobctl commit-work` (source commit), Phase 6 runs `planctl done` (state commit via hook). `done` is the last thing the worker fires — `status: done` from `planctl show` after the worker returns implies the source commit has already landed.
- `jobctl commit-work` failures (lint, commit, push) all surface as `BLOCKED: TOOLING_FAILURE` with the verbatim envelope. Workers do not patch the tool they're calling, even if it has a real bug — the human files a separate task. The flock at `$GIT_COMMON_DIR/jobctl-commit.lock` prevents intra-host races; the human resolves cross-host push failures and re-runs.
- **Never auto-retries a semantic failure** (worker returned `BLOCKED: <CATEGORY>`) — surface and stop. Lint auto-fix and similar tooling-recovery niceties belong in `jobctl commit-work` itself, not in this skill.
- Harness drops auto-recover via Phase 2b's recovery budget — **5 attempts (1 spawn + 4 retries)**, warm SendMessage resume in-session or cold fresh-spawn cross-session, each attempt counting toward the budget. The budget is best-effort per-invocation (warm retries are counted in-memory; cold-resume invocations each get their own budget — no attempt count is persisted on the task). Only after the 5th attempt drops does the task flip to `blocked`+`RESUME_EXHAUSTED` — stop and surface.
- **Tier routing is owned by keeper + planner, not this skill.** `/plan:plan` picks tier at decomposition time and writes it onto the task. Keeper reads it from its own projected Task data pre-boot and loads `claude/work-plugins/<tier>/`. This skill spawns `Task(subagent_type="work:worker")` as a bare literal — no tier-picking, no `task set-tier` write, no cold-resume tier-read. fn-594: scaffold / refine-apply now reject missing tier at mint time, so the only remaining null-tier surface is pre-fn-594 legacy on-disk records; keeper fails loud on them with `task <id> has unsupported tier ...`, and humans remediate via `/plan:plan <epic_id>` refine.
- **Phase 4 attribution: `session_files`, not `status_porcelain`.** The repo runs concurrent agents and the human in parallel. Anything in the dirty tree that isn't in this session's `session_files` belongs to someone else — never inspect, classify, or commit it.
- **`done` + dirty paths in this session's `session_files` is an unexpected state.** With commit-before-done, this can't happen on a happy path. If observed, surface verbatim and stop — never auto-resume, never auto-commit.
- **Never reads or writes** anywhere outside planctl state + project code.
- Never use `TodoWrite` — planctl tracks all tasks.

